<br>
When I started the quest, I did some research in order to get a feel for what it required of the player.  As you may have guessed, I anticipated a considerable amount of difficulty in completing the quest.  So I accordingly adjusted my mindset.  I started with the &quot;easier&quot; parts (with some help when needed), until I got to about the last four or five items.  <br>
<br>
Our guild was doing Hate raids every now and then during the last school year.  I still needed--er, wanted--the staff from that zone.  However, instead of hoping/praying that the Magi would be up with a staff, I simply ported up with the assumption that it'd be a very long time before I ever saw him, with or without the staff (ok, so I was wrong).  That way, I wasn't even concerned about whether he was up or not.  It essentially freed me from my desire for the staff, and thus helped to make it very easy to stay for the duration of the raid (not to mention that it was quite fun to raid with friends; friends&gt;ph4t l3wts).<br>
<br>
I still don't think the quest &quot;reward&quot; is worth wrecking yourself.   I think that it's important to manage your stress, and doing this quest doesn't seem to help many people do that.  I also see time as a scarce resource; i.e., you're only given so much time within which to operate.  That's why I took the aforementioned approach to getting the Hate staff.  I didn't see any reason for which I should have spent too much time trying to obtain it.  I don't think that the time that I did spend in Hate was wasted, because I was able to enjoy it.<br>
<br>
In spite of all this, I must admit that after acquiring the Hate staff, I experienced a rekindling of the desire to further pursue the quest (which isn't to say that I'd given up, but rather that I'd expected to get stuck there).  It was a good feeling, though, so I guess I'm pleased with my approach.  Besides, with college starting this fall, I won't have as much time to play with what might have otherwise been the product of hundreds of hours of time spent chasing after rare mobs/drops.  <br>
<br>
I had a lot of help, but I still think that maintaining a certain attitude proved to be just as important as the help I received from every one of the kind people who gave me their assistance.<br>
